# This demultiplexing tool comes from Guillaume Jospin's scripts, which
# are available here :
#    https://github.com/gjospin/scripts
#
# This script requires Trimmomatic and flash. The flash binary can be
# installed anywhere, as long as it is in $PATH.
#
#    http://ccb.jhu.edu/software/FLASH/
#
# The path to the Trimmomatic jar file has to be passed to the script 
# directly using the --trim-tool option, and the jar file MUST be 
# nammed 'trimmomatic.jar'. I did this with a simlink, like so :
#
# http://www.usadellab.org/cms/?page=trimmomatic
# unzip Trimmomatic-0.32.zip
# cd Trimmomatic-0.32 
# ln -s trimmomatic-0.32.jar trimmomatic.jar

!perl raw/Demul_trim_prep.pl \
--trim-file ../barcodes/adapter_all_16s.txt \
--trim-tool /home/russell/pkg/Trimmomatic-0.32/ \
--read-len 300 \
--frag-len 253 \
--reverse \
raw fishpoo_map.tsv demul fishpoo &> demul.log

# lump all the files together again
!cat demul/qiime_ready/fishpoo.M.*.faa > $demuldata

# Adjsut the sequence orientation so the reast of QIIME will work

!adjust_seq_orientation.py -i $demuldata -o fishpoo.fasta

import csv

colnames, rownames = [],[]
table = []
with open("fishpoo_phase1_otus.csv") as f :
    for n,row in enumerate(csv.reader(f)) :
        if n == 0 : rownames = row; continue
        colnames.append(row[0])
        table.append(map(int, row[1:]))

table = array(table)
sampleID = {}
with open("fishpoo_map.tsv") as f :
    for n,row in enumerate(csv.reader(f, delimiter='\t')) :
        if n == 0 : continue
        if not row[6] == 'Phase I' : continue 
        sampleID[row[0]] = row[13]

# merge replicates, normalize OTU counts to continuously variable
# traits totalling to 100 per host
mergeddata = {}
for n,name in enumerate(rownames) :
    if not mergeddata.has_key(sampleID[name]) :
        mergeddata[sampleID[name]] = zeros(len(colnames))
    mergeddata[sampleID[name]] = map(float, table[:,n])
for key in mergeddata.keys() :
    mergeddata[key] = 100 * ( mergeddata[key] / sum(mergeddata[key]) )

f = open( 'fishpoo_phase1_otus_vs_host.csv', 'w' )
f.write(','.join(colnames) + '\n' )
for n,name in enumerate(mergeddata.keys()) :
    if name == "Food" : continue
    if name == "Charcoal_control" : continue
    if name == "Control_1" : continue
    if name == "Kit_control" : continue
    if name == "Water_control" : continue
    f.write(name + ',' + ','.join( map(str, mergeddata[name] ) ) + '\n' )
f.close()

Host tree

Despite having only 14 taxa, it's been surprisingly difficult to build a trustworthy phylogeny of my fish. So, I am instead using a huge published phylogeny, and pruning it to 14 taxa.

Four of my fish aren't in the published tree, so I am using sister species as stand-ins. These groups are mostly polytomies just above the genus level, so... hopefully that's OK.

%%R -w 800 -h 480 -u px

# stochastic character mapping

library("phytools")

# use make.simmap() for categorical data : http://www.inside-r.org/packages/cran/phytools/docs/make.simmap
# use contMap() for continious data : http://www.inside-r.org/node/166056

# we need this function to change the color mapping...
# code is from here : http://blog.phytools.org/2014/12/inverting-color-map-on-object-of-class.html
setMap<-function(x,...){
    if(hasArg(invert)) invert<-list(...)$invert
    else invert<-FALSE
    n<-length(x$cols)
    if(invert) x$cols<-setNames(rev(x$cols),names(x$cols))
    else x$cols[1:n]<-colorRampPalette(...)(n)
    x
}

obj <- contMap( rabosky_trimmed, as.matrix(phase1_otus)[,"X828162"], plot=FALSE )
plot(setMap(obj,invert=TRUE))

Distribution of Aeromonas

One OTU, annotatd as an Aeromonas, dominates the dataset, and is the most abundant OTU for every single host. However, its distribution across the host phylogeny is still very uneven, and some patterns are evident

What's next

The most interesting systems to study using these methods are ones where we have lots of metadata about the system itself. Those are where we can potentially gain the most powerful insights.

This poses some methodological challenges. It's easy to overconstrain the data.
